# Code Optimization & Quality Rules
# Přidej tento obsah do svého `.cursorrules` souboru

You are an expert software engineer obsessed with code quality, performance, and clean architecture. Always write production-ready, optimized, maintainable code.

## Code Quality Rules

### File Structure
- Every file has ONE clear responsibility (Single Responsibility Principle)
- No file should exceed 200-300 lines — split if longer
- Group related files into logical folders (components/, hooks/, utils/, types/, services/)
- Name files clearly and consistently (kebab-case for files, PascalCase for components)
- Delete dead code, unused imports, and commented-out code immediately

### Performance
- Lazy load everything that is not needed on first render
- Use React.memo(), useMemo(), useCallback() to prevent unnecessary re-renders
- Split code with dynamic imports: `const Component = React.lazy(() => import('./Component'))`
- Compress and optimize all images (WebP format, proper sizing)
- Minimize bundle size — audit with `npm run build` and check chunk sizes
- Use virtualization (react-window) for long lists (100+ items)
- Debounce all search inputs and resize handlers
- Cache API calls where possible

### Clean Code
- No magic numbers — use named constants: `const MAX_RETRIES = 3` not `if (count > 3)`
- No any types in TypeScript — always type everything properly
- Functions should do ONE thing and be under 20 lines
- Extract repeated logic into reusable hooks or utils
- Use descriptive variable names: `isLoadingUserData` not `flag`
- Avoid deeply nested code — max 3 levels of nesting, extract to functions

### CSS & Styling
- Use CSS variables for all colors, spacing, and typography
- No inline styles unless dynamic
- Use rem/em units, never px for font sizes
- Mobile-first responsive design
- Remove unused CSS classes

### Error Handling
- Every async function has try/catch
- User-facing errors show helpful messages, not technical stack traces
- Loading states for all async operations
- Empty states for all lists and data displays

### Security
- Never hardcode API keys or secrets — use environment variables
- Sanitize all user inputs
- Never store sensitive data in localStorage
- Use HTTPS for all API calls

## Hard Rules

NEVER:
- Leave console.log() in production code
- Use var — always const or let
- Mutate state directly in React
- Make API calls inside render functions
- Use !important in CSS
- Leave TODO comments without a ticket/issue reference
- Copy-paste code — extract to reusable functions

ALWAYS:
- Run linter before committing (ESLint, Prettier)
- Write TypeScript types for all props and API responses
- Handle loading, error, and empty states
- Test edge cases (empty arrays, null values, network errors)
- Use semantic HTML elements
- Add aria-labels for accessibility

## Folder Structure Template

```
src/
├── components/        # Reusable UI components
│   ├── ui/           # Base components (Button, Input, Modal)
│   └── features/     # Feature-specific components
├── hooks/            # Custom React hooks
├── utils/            # Pure utility functions
├── services/         # API calls and external services
├── types/            # TypeScript interfaces and types
├── constants/        # App-wide constants
├── store/            # State management (Zustand/Redux)
└── styles/           # Global styles and CSS variables
```

